classes.title: ANCIENT GREEKS
classes.description: An introduction to the literature and culture of ancient Greece. The study of literary and material remains will illustrate how the Greeks lived and the values they expressed through literature and the arts. Topics may include the rituals and festivals of Greek religion, the conflict between heroic ideals and democratic ideology, the institutions that shaped public and private life, and the competitive nature of law, drama, athletics and politics.

classes.title: ANC GREEKS - HONORS
classes.description: A discussion section led by the instructor, provided for students in the ho nors program. Students receive one unit for the honors seminar (20AH) in ad dition to four units for Classics 20A.

classes.title: GREEK MYTHOLOGY
classes.description: Introduction to the principal myths of ancient Greece and the ways in whichthese myths have been understood. Format and readings vary.

classes.title: GREEK MYTH-HONORS
classes.description: A discussion section led by the professor is available to students in the honors program. Students will receive one unit for the honors seminar (40H)in addition to four units for Classics 40.

classes.title: INTRO ARCHAEOLOGY
classes.description: Examines the techniques and methods of classical archaeology as revealed through an examination of the major monuments and artifacts of the Greco-Roman world from prehistory to the Late Empire.

classes.title: INTRO TO RESEARCH
classes.description: Directed study, oriented toward research, to be arranged with individual faculty members. Course offers exceptional students an opportunity to participate in a research project or group.

classes.title: ANCIENT SLAVERY
classes.description: Examination of the nature and impact of chattel slavery in the ancient Mediterranean, with emphasis on classical Greece and imperial Rome. How did ancient thinkers like Aristotle and Seneca define slavery in opposition to freedom? What modes of slave labor thrived in antiquity and why? How did the enslaved resist subjugation, whether through outright rebellion like the revolt led by Spartacus or by other means? Primary sources and comparative evidence will guide discussion of these and other key questions.

classes.title: FALL ANC REPUBLIC
classes.description: The tumultuous end of the Roman Republic, from Tiberius Gracchus (133 BC) to the Rubicon (49 BC), had profound importance for the history of the West and produced a fascinating literature of crisis in the writings of Sallust, Cicero, Catullus, and Caesar.

classes.title: HONORS THESIS
classes.description: Research and writing of a senior thesis paper under the close supervision of a Classics faculty member.

classes.title: SPECIAL READINGS
classes.description: Individual or small group reading and study in subjects not included in theregular curriculum.

classes.title: INDEPENDENT STUDIES
classes.description: Independent study in areas in which both Greek and Latin are necessary.

classes.title: INDEPEND. RESEARCH
classes.description: To cooperate on an active basis with a professor on a research project involving the Classics.
